[[ja:相輪橖]][[nl:Sōrintō]] {|class="vatop" style="border:solid thin slategray;background-color:aliceblue;font-size:90%;" align="right" !colspan=6 style="font-size:120%;"| The components of the sōrin from top to bottom: |- | || || || ||rowspan=10| [[Bestand:Tenneiji Onomichi03s3200-Sourin.jpg|300px|center]] |- | '''hōju''' || ||宝珠 || 'sacred jewel' |- | '''ryūsha''' || ||竜車 || 'dragon wheel' |- | '''suien''' || ||水煙 || 'water flame' |- | '''sakkan''' || || || column, with: |- |… '''fūtaku''' || ||風鐸, ふうたく || wind chimes |- |… '''kurin''' || ||九輪 || nine rings |- | '''ukebana''' || ||受花 || {{nowrap|'receiving flower'}} |- | '''fukubachi'''|| ||伏鉢 || inverted bowl |- | '''roban''' || ||露盤 || 'dew basin' |}
The '''Sōrintō''' ({{ill|Sōrintō|sōrintō|sōrintō|ja|相輪橖|zh|相轮韬}}, {{ill|Sōrintō|sōrintō|sōrintō|ja|相輪塔|zh|相轮塔}}, そうりんとう) is a type of small {{ill|pagoda|pagode|pagoda|ja|塔|zh|塔}} that consists solely of a pillar (''sao'') and a sōrin. The sōrintō is also known as the Aiwa- or Siwa-pagoda.
A '''sōrin''' ({{ill|sōrin|sōrin|sōrin|ja|相輪|zh|相轮}}) is the most important part of the pagoda. It is also the spire or finial—the vertical axis—that usually serves as a decorative element rising above the pagoda’s roof. The sōrin is made of metal (bronze or iron) and is either placed atop a wooden pagoda or carved into a stone pagoda (''sekitō''). Typically, the sōrin consists of several parts: at its base is the box-shaped dew basin (''roban'') surmounted by the inverted bowl (''fukubachi''); above this is a column (''sakkan'') bearing nine rings (''kurin'', 空輪 or ''hōrin'' (宝輪)) which may be adorned with wind chimes (''fūtaku''), then the water flame (''suien''), and finally the dragon wheel (''ryūsha'', not found on stone pagodas, ''sekitō''), crowned with the sacred jewel (''hōju'').
'''Kūrin''' ({{ill|Kūrin|Kūrin|Kūrin|ja|九輪|zh|九轮}}, or '''hōrin''' (宝輪)) is a component of the top of a pagoda, namely the sōrin. Typically, nine metal rings are affixed to the cylindrical metal casing that covers the tapering central pillar extending above the pagoda’s roof. These rings may be decorated with wind chimes (''fūtaku'').
{{clearright}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="260px" perrow="4" class="center" caption="Images"> Hitsujisaki jinja Sourintou.JPG|A ''sorintō'' at Hitsujisaki {{ill|shrine|heiligdom|shrine|ja|神社|zh|神社}} 20190121 Tōdai-ji sōrin-1.jpg|A ''sorintō'' at Tōdai-ji Sorinto.jpg|''Sōrintō'', where the rings are adorned with wind chimes (''fūtaku''). Sorinto LACMA M.91.377.71.jpg|LACMA (1865) Sorinto of Rinno Temple.jpg|Rinno Temple Sorinto of Sairen-ji Temple in Namegata city,IBARAKI,Japan.jpg|Sairen-ji Temple in {{ill|Namegata|Namegata|Namegata|ja|名潟|zh|名潟}} Sorinto Tower in Dazaifu Temman Shrine.jpg|''Sōrintō'' at {{ill|Dazaifu Temman Shrine|Dazaifu Temman Shrine|Dazaifu Temman Shrine|ja|太宰府天満宮|zh|太宰府天満宮}} Murouji gojyunoto sorin.jpg|Murōji ''gojū-no-tō'' with a ''sōrin'' on the roof </gallery>
